entry.title: Rename {absl => std}::optional in //ash/
entry.content:
Automated patch, intended to be effectively a no-op.



Context:

https://groups.google.com/a/chromium.org/g/cxx/c/nBD_1LaanTc/m/ghh-ZZhWAwAJ?utm_medium=email&utm_source=footer



As of https://crrev.com/1204351, absl::optional is now a type alias for

std::optional. We should migrate toward it.



Script:

```

function replace {

echo "Replacing $1 by $2"

git grep -l "$1" \

| cut -f1 -d: \

| grep \

-e "^ash" \

| sort \

| uniq \

| grep \

-e "\.h" \

-e "\.cc" \

-e "\.mm" \

-e "\.py" \

| xargs sed -i "s/$1/$2/g"

}

replace "absl::make_optional" "std::make_optional"

replace "absl::optional" "std::optional"

replace "absl::nullopt" "std::nullopt"

replace "absl::in_place" "std::in_place"

replace "absl::in_place_t" "std::in_place_t"

replace "\"third_party\/abseil-cpp\/absl\/types\/optional.h\"" ""

git cl format

```

powerless, and treated as missing when converted into LCH or Oklch

Rewrite the ControlledHomeBubbleDelegate as a

ToolbarActionsBarBubbleDelegate. In practice, this is already the way

the bubble was displayed by virtue of the ExtensionMessageBubbleBridge

(which bridged between ToolbarActionsBarBubbleDelegate and

ExtensionMessageBubbleController).



This allows us to get rid of a ton of old code for showing

extension bubbles.



Notable differences between the old and new controlled home bubbles

(none should result in user-visible changes):

* ExtensionMessageBubbleController had an idea of an "active bubble"

associated with the ToolbarActionsModel (one-per-profile). However,

since the controlled home bubble is the only bubble that uses this

(the other ExtensionMessageBubbleController usages have not been

used in years), this didn't perform any real coordination or

prevent any bubbles from overlapping. The new version instead

relies on a local set of profiles for which the bubble has been

shown, which is sufficient to prevent multiple controlled home bubbles

from appearing (feature parity with the old behavior).

* ExtensionMessageBubbleController was a BrowserListObserver and

reset the active bubble bit in the ToolbarActionsModel when the

browser went away. Since we no longer use that active bubble bit,

this class isn't a BrowserListObserver.

* Unit tests added are far more targeted and cover a wider variety of

test cases and behaviors.

* There's a delay between when we queue up the bubble to show and when

it shows; this is due to animation in the toolbar. During this time,

it's possible the extension is uninstalled. The

ExtensionMessageBubbleController would have undefined behavior in this

case; the new code handles it by closing the bubble right away.

entry.title: Remove an unnecessary bind in ash::CursorView.
entry.content:
There is no need to bind a repeating callback in the constructor and

then bind another callback when posting the result back to the UI

thread. This is strictly less efficient than just binding once, when

posting the task: callback has no "rebinding" mechanism, so nested binds

generate more object code and multiple forwarding trampolines.



Destruction of the `CursorView` is already synchronized with calls to

`OnCursorLocationChanged()`; otherwise, even `set_location_callback_`

cannot be safely used, the way it was before this CL. Because of this,

it is equally safe to call `WeakPtrFactory::GetWeakPtr()` from

`OnCursorLocationChanged()`: `GetWeakPtr()` is sequence-safe, as long as

it is synchronized with calls to `InvalidateWeakPtrs()` or destruction.

entry.title: [ios] Fix order in which recently closed tabs are cleared
entry.content:
When deleting browsing data, start by clearing the previous session

of "recently closed tabs" before purging the in-memory session. The

reason is that some observers of TabRestoreService force it to load

the last session on any changes (possibly incorrect behaviour, but

outside of the scope of this CL). This resulted in only clearing

data in memory, not all the data.



Fix this by first clearing the session on disk, and then clearing

the in-memory data. This way, even if observers ask to load data

from disk, there won't be anything to load.

entry.title: [sync] Allow auto-start even if sync disabled via dashboard on Ash
entry.content:
This is a minor behavioral change to avoid special-casing the rare

scenario where sync was disabled via dashboard on Ash and, upon profile

startup, no sync metadata exists.



The latter condition should be extra rare because, even if sync (the

feature) was disabled via dashboard, sync-the-transport gets activated

anyway and will quickly populate sync metadata.



Although it's not obvious from the code diff, the removed code is only

reachable if ShouldAutoStartSyncFeature() returns true and

IsLocalSyncEnabled() returns false, which means that

IsSyncFeatureConsideredRequested() -now removed- is equivalent to

!user_settings_->IsSyncFeatureDisabledViaDashboard(), representing the

actual behavioral difference.



As per rationale above, there is no good reason to keep complexity in

the logic and the call to IsSyncFeatureConsideredRequested() can be

avoided altogether.

entry.title: [//gpu] Move ownership of GpuMemoryBuffer into ClientSI
entry.content:
This CL changes ownership of the GpuMemoryBuffers associated with

MappableSharedImages from the SII implementations that create those

MappableSharedImages to the created ClientSharedImages. The lifetimes

in all cases are unchanged with one important assumption: that callers

of CreateSharedImage(BufferUsage) end up calling

DestroySharedImage(ClientSI) rather than DestroySharedImage(Mailbox)

[*]. This is true for all existing clients, and we will ensure that it

continues to be true as we convert more clients to MappableSharedImage.

(Note: the one exception is if the entire SII implementation gets torn

down before the client calls DestroySharedImage(ClientSI) on a given

ClientSI. We will need to handle that in the fullness of time, but in

the meantime, clients already can't effectively do anything with the

ClientSI/Mailbox once the SII is torn down).



* This is important because the destruction of the GMB now occurs when

the ClientSI is destroyed. If the client calls

DestroySharedImage(ClientSI), then the GMB is guaranteed to be destroyed

when the Mailbox is destroyed as is happening now. If the client calls

DestroySharedImage(Mailbox), the destruction of the GMB will occur

whenever the client happens to drop the ClientSI. This would presumably

still be OK as the client needs to have the ClientSI to call

MapSharedImage() in any case, but it's harder to reason about.



Bug: 1500611

entry.title: Properly resume content pushed by interleaved float.
entry.content:
A float may be interleaved by other content, if a break is inserted

before the block-end padding/border of the float. Then there may be room

available to other content below the content-box of the float in one

fragmentainer. If the remaining part of the float (i.e. the block-end

padding/border) in the next fragmentainer is too tall for the other

content to resume there, we might not make any progress at all there. In

such cases we need to repropagate any incoming child break tokens that

we didn't get to handle and retry in a fragmentainer further ahead.

entry.content:
To simplify the folder hierarchy on iOS and have a clearer layer

separation, all the files in ios/c/b// will be moved to

ios/c/b//model/ to showcase that they are model files.



We use an hybrid approach for migrating upstream and downstream

smoothly. Here we keep dependencies (only a few) used by internal in

the legacy folder, then we will change internal to use the new model/ folder for these dependencies, which weren't yet migrated. The

upstream code will use a forwarder header in model/ that forwards to

the remaining definitions in the legacy folder, up until the

migration is fully completed. Upstream clients of the ios/c/b/follow

modules are already fully migrated to ios/c/b/follow/model.



This CL is part of the chain of CLs for the model/ migration:

#1 Migrate downstream and use forwarder where needed: THIS

#2 Use model/ in internal: crrev.com/i/6706632 (tested)

#3 Finish the migration of the not yet migrated dependencies.

entry.title: [GridNG] Enforce GridPlacementData as output-only
entry.content:
1. Fixing a bug in `GridNode::ConstructGridItems` where we always

discarded the placement cache because the comparison method in

`GridPlacementData`, meant to be used exclusively to validate such

cache, was being used to check if the input placement data matched

the cache itself. This was ill-conceived since the input placement

data had default constructed values for output-only fields.



This was causing us to re-resolve the grid lines for every grid item,

even though placement ended up being the same as in the previous run.



2. This CL fixes the issue by refactoring uses of `GridPlacementData` as

an input parameter to pass the intended `GridLineResolver` instead.

- fixed-grid-lots-of-data

- fixed-grid-lots-of-stretched-data

entry.title: Fix IsCreditCardUploadEnabled() wrt transport mode
entry.content:
IsCreditCardUploadEnabled() decide whether credit card save can be

offered, depending on whether address Autofill is enabled (and various

other things). This check depends on kSyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings

and kSyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode - feature flags

controlling whether the address and payments settings toggles are

coupled, and whether address sync is available in transport mode.



Currently, the logic is wrong on iOS, as outlined in the bug.



This CL simplifies the check to

bool IsCreditCardUploadEnabled() {

...

bool syncing_or_addresses_in_transport_mode =

sync_service->IsSyncFeatureActive() ||

base::FeatureList::IsEnabled(

kSyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode);

if (syncing_or_addresses_in_transport_mode &&

!sync_service->GetUserSettings()->GetSelectedTypes().Has(

UserSelectableType::kAutofill)) {

...

return false;

}

}



This is correct in every scenario:

- kSyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode disabled

- Upload possible for all users in transport mode.

- In sync mode, upload possible for all users that haven't explicitly

disabled "Addresses and more" in sync settings.

When kSyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings is disabled, this is

effectively all users, since they otherwise can't have payment sync

enabled.

- kSyncEnableContactInfoDataTypeInTransportMode enabled (in particular,

the current state on iOS)

- No distinction between syncing and transport mode users.

- Like in the case above, upload possible for all users that haven't

explicitly disabled address sync. Whether this is possible at all

depends on kSyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings.



----



Some comments about the current logic: Currently, the code checks for

base::FeatureList::IsEnabled(kSyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings)

? sync_service->GetUserSettings()->GetSelectedTypes().Has(

UserSelectableType::kAutofill)

: sync_service->GetActiveDataTypes().Has(AUTOFILL_PROFILE)



That is, depending on kSyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings, either

default to the the status quo prior to crrev.com/c/4941899, or check for

the UserSelectableType.



In that sense, this CL regresses the behavior of checking for

AUTOFILL_PROFILE for syncing users. This is intended and arguably

desirable: AUTOFILL_WALLET_DATA can only be enabled when

AUTOFILL_PROFILE is enabled. This is already checked a few lines

above by the code. Prior to kSyncDecoupleAddressPaymentSettings, this

entire code block was only reachable for:

- Custom passphrase users, that haven't entered their passphrase yet.

In this case, card upload is disabled due to a check further down in

the function anyways.

- For users where AUTOFILL_PROFILE for some reason failed to start. This

happens extremely rarely, because AUTOFILL_PROFILE doesn't have

preconditions. Arguably, when AUTOFILL_PROFILE failed to start for

infrastructure reasons, there's no need to disable upload, since the

users explicitly has address syncing enabled from settings.



Fixed: 1504739
